************** G E N E R A L   I N F O R M A T I O N *************3231 1451   22
                                                                  3231 1451   23
This evaluated data file is based on a software system built      3231 1451   24
around the nuclear model code TALYS [kon23], version 2.0. It is   3231 1451   25
part of a large collection of isotopic evaluations, all created by3231 1451   26
running the system with either adjusted or default input          3231 1451   27
parameters. This means that the data in the entire collection have3231 1451   28
been tested in detail for many isotopes against individual        3231 1451   29
experimental data, while for other isotopes it is only as good as 3231 1451   30
the global quality of TALYS at the moment. The mutual quality of  3231 1451   31
all individual data files is however consistent: The same set of  3231 1451   32
nuclear models is used and, equally important, the same ENDF-6    3231 1451   33
formatting procedures for each isotope. The data file has been    3231 1451   34
created automatically using the ENDF-6 format generator TEFAL.    3231 1451   35
                                                                  3231 1451   36
The resulting data file provides a complete representation of     3231 1451   37
nuclear data needed for transport, activation, damage, heating,   3231 1451   38
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       3231 1451   39
neutron energy range from 1.e-11 to 200. MeV.                     3231 1451   40
                                                                  3231 1451   41
All transport and activation data for neutrons, charged particles,3231 1451   42
photons and residual nuclides are filed. This includes cross      3231 1451   43
sections, angular distributions, double-differential spectra,     3231 1451   44
isomeric production, discrete and continuum photon production     3231 1451   45
cross sections, residual production cross sections and recoils.   3231 1451   46
This general purpose evaluation can thus be used as both          3231 1451   47
transport and activation library.                                 3231 1451   48
                                                                  3231 1451   49
A complete set of covariance data is included, which is stored    3231 1451   50
in MF31-40.                                                       3231 1451   51
                                                                  3231 1451   52
                      Resonance Range                             3231 1451   53
                                                                  3231 1451   54
  --------------------------------------------------------------- 3231 1451   55
  --------------------------------------------------------------- 3231 1451   56
                                                                  3231 1451   57
  General methodology: The global approach considered in this     3231 1451   58
          work is presented in the following papers:              3231 1451   59
          (1) Modern nuclear data evaluation with the TALYS       3231 1451   60
              code system, A.J. Koning and D. Rochman,            3231 1451   61
              A.J. Koning and D. Rochman,                         3231 1451   62
              Nuclear Data Sheets 113 (2012) 2841.                3231 1451   63
          (2) TENDL: Complete Nuclear Data Library for            3231 1451   64
              Innovative Nuclear Science and Technology,          3231 1451   65
              A.J. Koning, D. Rochman, J.Ch Sublet, N. Dzysiuk,   3231 1451   66
              M. Fleming and S. van der Marck,                    3231 1451   67
              Nuclear Data Sheets 155 (2019) 1.                   3231 1451   68
                                                                  3231 1451   69
  MF2:  Resolved resonance range  (RRR)                           3231 1451   70
       The RRR was generated with TARES-1.4                       3231 1451   71
       The unresolved resonance range is obtained from the TALYS  3231 1451   72
       code.                                                      3231 1451   73
                                                                  3231 1451   74
  MF33 in the resonance range:                                    3231 1451   75
  The MF33 in the resonance range is obtained by using a number   3231 1451   76
  of MF2 random files. There is therefore a consistency           3231 1451   77
  between the MF2 random and the MF33.                            3231 1451   78
  MF32:                                                           3231 1451   79
  The MF32 contains the resonance parameters, uncertainties and   3231 1451   80
  some correlation. These values are used to generate random      3231 1451   81
  MF2, taking advantage of the code ENDSAM from L. Plevnik and    3231 1451   82
  G. Zerovnik from JSI, Slovenia (thanks to A. Trkov, IAEA).      3231 1451   83
                                                                  3231 1451   84
***************************** T A L Y S **************************3231 1451   85
                                                                  3231 1451   86
TALYS is a computer code system for the prediction and analysis   3231 1451   87
of nuclear reactions. TALYS simulates reactions that involve      3231 1451   88
neutrons, gamma-rays, protons, deuterons, tritons, helions and    3231 1451   89
alpha-particles, in the 1 keV - 200 MeV energy range. This is     3231 1451   90
achieved by implementing a suite of nuclear reaction models into  3231 1451   91
a single code system. This nuclear data file is based on a        3231 1451   92
theoretical analysis that utilizes the optical model, compound    3231 1451   93
nucleus statistical theory, fission, direct reactions and         3231 1451   94
pre-equilibrium processes, in combination with databases and      3231 1451   95
models for nuclear structure. The following output of TALYS is    3231 1451   96
stored in this data file:                                         3231 1451   97
                                                                  3231 1451   98
- Total, elastic and non-elastic cross sections                   3231 1451   99
- Inelastic cross sections to discrete states                     3231 1451  100
- Exclusive channel cross sections, e.g. (n,g), (n,2n), (n,np),.. 3231 1451  101
- Inelastic scattering angular distributions to discrete states   3231 1451  102
- Exclusive channel energy spectra                                3231 1451  103
- Exclusive channel double-differential spectra                   3231 1451  104
- Exclusive gamma production for discrete states and continuum    3231 1451  105
- Elastic scattering angular distributions                        3231 1451  106
- Recoil data                                                     3231 1451  107
- Total particle cross sections, e.g. (n,xn), (n,xp),..           3231 1451  108
- Total particle energy spectra                                   3231 1451  109
- Total particle double-differential spectra                      3231 1451  110
- Isomeric and ground state cross sections                        3231 1451  111
- Residual production cross sections                              3231 1451  112
                                                                  3231 1451  113
For a description of the used nuclear models and their            3231 1451  114
parameterization we refer to [kon19]. If for this specific        3231 1451  115
nuclide we deviate from the global parameterization, it is made   3231 1451  116
explicit above under Nuclide Specific Information.                3231 1451  117
                                                                  3231 1451  118
***************** F I L E   I N F O R M A T I O N ****************3231 1451  119
