##### MF1: GENERAL INFORMATION                                    3231 1451  121
                                                                  3231 1451  122
- MT451    : Descriptive data and directory                       3231 1451  123
                                                                  3231 1451  124
This text and the full directory of used MF/MT sections.          3231 1451  125
                                                                  3231 1451  126
##### MF2: RESONANCE PARAMETERS                                   3231 1451  127
                                                                  3231 1451  128
- MT151    : Resonance parameters                                 3231 1451  129
                                                                  3231 1451  130
Details about the origin of the resonance parameters for this     3231 1451  131
nuclide are given above in this description. In general, both a   3231 1451  132
Resolved and an Unresolved Resonance Range are given.             3231 1451  133
                                                                  3231 1451  134
##### MF3: REACTION CROSS SECTIONS                                3231 1451  135
                                                                  3231 1451  136
All the data present in the following MT-sections have been       3231 1451  137
calculated with TALYS, possibly normalized to experimental data.  3231 1451  138
If the maximal cross section in an excitation function over the   3231 1451  139
whole energy range does not exceed 1.e-9 b, the MT-number is not  3231 1451  140
included. Cross sections lower than 1.e-20 b are assumed to have  3231 1451  141
no physical meaning and are set to zero. All MT numbers extend up 3231 1451  142
to the highest incident energy.                                   3231 1451  143
The following reaction channels/MT numbers are generally included:3231 1451  144
                                                                  3231 1451  145
- MT1      : Total cross section                                  3231 1451  146
                                                                  3231 1451  147
Calculated with the optical model over the whole energy range,    3231 1451  148
or partly reproduced using experimental data.                     3231 1451  149
                                                                  3231 1451  150
- MT2      : Elastic scattering cross section                     3231 1451  151
                                                                  3231 1451  152
Obtained by subtracting the non-elastic cross section from the    3231 1451  153
total cross section.                                              3231 1451  154
                                                                  3231 1451  155
- MT3      : Non-elastic cross section                            3231 1451  156
                                                                  3231 1451  157
Calculated with the optical model over the whole energy range.    3231 1451  158
                                                                  3231 1451  159
- MT4      : Total inelastic cross section                        3231 1451  160
                                                                  3231 1451  161
Sum of MT=51-91.                                                  3231 1451  162
                                                                  3231 1451  163
- MT5      : (n,anything) cross section                           3231 1451  164
                                                                  3231 1451  165
MT5 contains the reactions which can not be stored in any other   3231 1451  166
MT-number. The information of MF3/MT5 can be combined with        3231 1451  167
MF6/MT5 to obtain residual production cross sections particle     3231 1451  168
production cross sections and (double-)differential cross         3231 1451  169
sections.                                                         3231 1451  170
                                                                  3231 1451  171
- MT16     : (n,2n) cross section                                 3231 1451  172
- MT17     : (n,3n) cross section                                 3231 1451  173
- MT22     : (n,na) cross section                                 3231 1451  174
- MT28     : (n,np) cross section                                 3231 1451  175
- MT51-90  : (n,n') cross section for 1st-40th excited state      3231 1451  176
- MT91     : (n,n') continuum cross section                       3231 1451  177
- MT102    : (n,gamma) cross section                              3231 1451  178
- MT103    : (n,p) cross section                                  3231 1451  179
- MT104    : (n,d) cross section                                  3231 1451  180
- MT105    : (n,t) cross section                                  3231 1451  181
- MT106    : (n,h) cross section                                  3231 1451  182
- MT107    : (n,a) cross section                                  3231 1451  183
- MT600-610: (n,p) cross section for 0th-10th excited state       3231 1451  184
- MT649    : (n,p) continuum cross section                        3231 1451  185
- MT650-655: (n,d) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        3231 1451  186
- MT699    : (n,d) continuum cross section                        3231 1451  187
- MT700-705: (n,t) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        3231 1451  188
- MT749    : (n,t) continuum cross section                        3231 1451  189
- MT750-755: (n,h) cross section for 0th-5th excited state        3231 1451  190
- MT799    : (n,h) continuum cross section                        3231 1451  191
- MT800-810: (n,a) cross section for 0th-10th excited state       3231 1451  192
- MT849    : (n,a) continuum cross section                        3231 1451  193
                                                                  3231 1451  194
##### MF4: ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS OF SECONDARY PARTICLES           3231 1451  195
                                                                  3231 1451  196
We use MF4 for the neutron scattering angular distribution for    3231 1451  197
discrete levels.                                                  3231 1451  198
                                                                  3231 1451  199
- MT2      : Elastic angular distribution                         3231 1451  200
                                                                  3231 1451  201
The flag LTT=3 is used to indicate a switch at some high energy,  3231 1451  202
generally 50 MeV, from a Legendre representation to a tabulated   3231 1451  203
representation. For incident energies below this energy, the      3231 1451  204
Legendre coefficients are given on a sufficiently precise energy  3231 1451  205
grid. They are a sum of calculated Legendre coefficients for      3231 1451  206
compound nucleus and shape-elastic scattering. For higher         3231 1451  207
incident energies, relative angular distributions are tabulated   3231 1451  208
on an angular grid.                                               3231 1451  209
                                                                  3231 1451  210
- MT51-70  : (n,n') angular distribution for 1st-20th state       3231 1451  211
- MT600-610: (n,p) angular distribution for 0th-10th state        3231 1451  212
- MT650-655: (n,d) angular distribution for 0th-5th state         3231 1451  213
- MT700-705: (n,t) angular distribution for 0th-5th state         3231 1451  214
- MT750-755: (n,h) angular distribution for 0th-5th state         3231 1451  215
- MT800-810: (n,a) angular distribution for 0th-10th state        3231 1451  216
                                                                  3231 1451  217
##### MF6: PRODUCT ENERGY-ANGLE DISTRIBUTIONS                     3231 1451  218
                                                                  3231 1451  219
In MF6 we store all secondary energy, angle, and energy-angle     3231 1451  220
distributions, as well as all residual and discrete + continuum   3231 1451  221
photon production cross sections for channels other than capture  3231 1451  222
(MT102) and reactions to discrete levels (MT51,etc.).             3231 1451  223
All data are generated with TALYS.                                3231 1451  224
                                                                  3231 1451  225
- MT5      : (n,anything) yields and energy-angle distributions   3231 1451  226
                                                                  3231 1451  227
MT5 contains, in this order,                                      3231 1451  228
For neutrons up to alpha particles and photons:                   3231 1451  229
- the production yields per particle for the whole energy range   3231 1451  230
- the secondary energy-angle distributions per particles which are3231 1451  231
  not represented by explicit MT numbers. On a secondary energy   3231 1451  232
  grid the relative emission spectra are given together with the  3231 1451  233
  parameters for the Kalbach systematics for angular              3231 1451  234
  distributions. Inelastic scattering cross sections for discrete 3231 1451  235
  states have been broadened and added to the continuum spectra.  3231 1451  236
For each residual product:                                        3231 1451  237
- the production yields for the whole energy range.               3231 1451  238
- the recoil                                                      3231 1451  239
These distributions can be multiplied with MF3/MT5 to get         3231 1451  240
the production cross sections and (double-)differential cross     3231 1451  241
sections.                                                         3231 1451  242
                                                                  3231 1451  243
- MT16     : (n,2n) energy-angle distr. and photon production     3231 1451  244
                                                                  3231 1451  245
First, for each type of outgoing particle, the (trivial) integer  3231 1451  246
particle yields are given. Next, on a sufficiently dense incident 3231 1451  247
energy grid the secondary energy-angle distributions are          3231 1451  248
specified by means of the relative emission spectra and the       3231 1451  249
parameters for the Kalbach systematics for angular distributions. 3231 1451  250
Next, the photon yield is tabulated as a function of incident     3231 1451  251
energy. For each incident energy, the photon production is given  3231 1451  252
for all discrete gamma lines present in the final nucleus. A      3231 1451  253
continuum photon distribution is added to this. We assume         3231 1451  254
isotropy for all produced gamma rays.                             3231 1451  255
                                                                  3231 1451  256
For the following MT-numbers, the same procedure as for MT16 is   3231 1451  257
followed:                                                         3231 1451  258
                                                                  3231 1451  259
- MT17 : (n,3n) energy-angle distr. and photon production         3231 1451  260
- MT22 : (n,na) energy-angle distr. and photon production         3231 1451  261
- MT28 : (n,np) energy-angle distr. and photon production         3231 1451  262
- MT91 : (n,n') continuum energy-angle distr. and phot. prod.     3231 1451  263
- MT649: (n,p) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     3231 1451  264
- MT699: (n,d) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     3231 1451  265
- MT749: (n,t) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     3231 1451  266
- MT809: (n,h) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     3231 1451  267
- MT849: (n,a) continuum energy-angle distr. and photon prod.     3231 1451  268
                                                                  3231 1451  269
##### MF8: RADIOACTIVE DECAY DATA                                 3231 1451  270
                                                                  3231 1451  271
For reactions to isomers, MF8 designates where the information    3231 1451  272
for isomeric versus ground state production, or residual          3231 1451  273
production can be found, i.e. for each MT number it points to     3231 1451  274
either MF6, MF9 or MF10.                                          3231 1451  275
                                                                  3231 1451  276
##### MF9: MULTIPLICITIES FOR PRODUCTION OF RADIOACTIVE NUCLIDES  3231 1451  277
                                                                  3231 1451  278
MF9 is used for isomer production by non-threshold reactions.     3231 1451  279
Final states with a lifetime that exceeds 1 second are treated    3231 1451  280
as isomer.                                                        3231 1451  281
                                                                  3231 1451  282
##### MF10: CROSS SECTIONS FOR PRODUCTION OF RADIOACTIVE NUCLIDES 3231 1451  283
                                                                  3231 1451  284
MF10 is used for isomer production by threshold reactions.        3231 1451  285
Final states with a lifetime that exceeds 1 second are treated    3231 1451  286
as isomer.                                                        3231 1451  287
                                                                  3231 1451  288
##### MF12: PHOTON PRODUCTION YIELD DATA                          3231 1451  289
                                                                  3231 1451  290
MF12 is used for the photon production for two types of reactions:3231 1451  291
- Reactions to discrete levels (MT51, etc.) For this transition   3231 1451  292
  probabilities are used (LO=2)                                   3231 1451  293
- Photons from neutron capture (MT102). Here multiplicities are   3231 1451  294
  given                                                           3231 1451  295
                                                                  3231 1451  296
##### MF14: PHOTON ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS                          3231 1451  297
                                                                  3231 1451  298
All photon production is considered as isotropic                  3231 1451  299
                                                                  3231 1451  300
##### MF15: PHOTON ENERGY SPECTRA                                 3231 1451  301
                                                                  3231 1451  302
For capture (MT102), the photon energy spectrum is given.         3231 1451  303
                                                                  3231 1451  304
##### MF32: COVARIANCES OF RESONANCE PARAMETERS                   3231 1451  305
                                                                  3231 1451  306
In MF32, we store the covariances of resonance parameters,        3231 1451  307
and more details are given above in this description. In most     3231 1451  308
versions of TENDL, this information is now stored in MF33.        3231 1451  309
                                                                  3231 1451  310
##### MF33: COVARIANCES OF NEUTRON CROSS SECTIONS                 3231 1451  311
                                                                  3231 1451  312
In MF33, we store the covariances of most, but not all, reaction  3231 1451  313
channels that are given in MF3. All covariances are generated     3231 1451  314
with the TASMAN code [kon19], which generates TALYS runs using    3231 1451  315
a Monte Carlo parameter method.                                   3231 1451  316
For each MT-number, the information consists of:                  3231 1451  317
1. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTa, Ea (variances)                3231 1451  318
2. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTa, Eb (correlations for the      3231 1451  319
   same reaction channel between different energies)              3231 1451  320
3. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTb, Ea (correlations between      3231 1451  321
   different reaction channels for the same energy)               3231 1451  322
4. Covariances for MTa, Ea and MTb, Eb (correlations between      3231 1451  323
   different reaction channels for different energies)            3231 1451  324
Classes 1 and 2 are covered by NI-type subsubsections with        3231 1451  325
flag LB=5, followed by a LB=8 section which contains              3231 1451  326
the cross section variances multiplied by 1.e-3. Next, classes 3  3231 1451  327
and 4 are covered by flag LB=6 to account for the different       3231 1451  328
energy grids that two correlating MT-sections may have. Since     3231 1451  329
the total correlation matrix is fully symmetric, we only need to  3231 1451  330
include the correlation elements between different MT-numbers     3231 1451  331
once, and we do that in the subsection with the lowest of the     3231 1451  332
two MT-numbers. We include covariance information for all the     3231 1451  333
total cross sections, the lumped partial cross sections and the   3231 1451  334
individual inelastic cross sections per level (MT51,...). We do   3231 1451  335
not include covariances for MT600 and higher MT-numbers. For the  3231 1451  336
most important channels, we include cross-channel correlations.   3231 1451  337
                                                                  3231 1451  338
##### MF34: COVARIANCES OF ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS                  3231 1451  339
                                                                  3231 1451  340
In MF34, we store the covariances of the elastic scattering       3231 1451  341
angular distributions that are given in MF4/MT2. All covariances  3231 1451  342
are generated with the TASMAN code [kon19], which generates       3231 1451  343
TALYS runs using a Monte Carlo parameter method. The tables are   3231 1451  344
restricted to MT2 and contain covariances for the first 6         3231 1451  345
Legendre coefficients. Both intra- and inter-correlations of the  3231 1451  346
various Legendre coefficients are given. As in MF33, the LB5      3231 1451  347
representation is used.                                           3231 1451  348
                                                                  3231 1451  349
##### MF40: COVARIANCES OF ISOMER PRODUCTION                      3231 1451  350
                                                                  3231 1451  351
For covariances of ground state and isomeric cross sections, the  3231 1451  352
same procedures as for MF33 are used.                             3231 1451  353
                                                                  3231 1451  354
